ce:section.ce:para:
Brunauer-Emmett-Teller (BET) analysis is a widely employed technique for determining the specific surface area (SBET) of materials by gas adsorption-desorption isotherm measurements. Here, nitrogen sorption was conducted at 77 K on the starch-derived CQDs (Fig. 5
                        ). The estimated SBET for the CQDs was 0.34 m2/g based on BET theory (Table 1
                        ). This negligible surface area indicates the likely absence of well-defined pores in the core CQD structure. Instead, the ultra-small CQDs nanodomains with sizes below 10 nm predominantly expose atomically smooth basal plane-like surfaces. While traditional porous carbons exploit high internal surface areas for adsorption, the pore-free CQDs can derive unique size-dependent optical, electronic, and catalytic properties directly from their non-porous quasi-0-D structure. Further surface engineering of these starch-derived CQDs by adding charged or chemically reactive functional groups can enhance their physicochemical properties and expand their applicability.
